[0.433, "o", "\u001b[H\n \u001b[38;2;204;204;204mbrokering inherited/shared namespace activity or the snapshot is aggregating more than the script alone. No obvious injected\u001b[m  \u001b[K\r\n \u001b[38;2;204;204;204mlibrary or odd binary swap is present: get_maps shows normal Python/libc/libm/libffi modules, goread_environ is ordinary\u001b[m      \u001b[K\r\n \u001b[38;2;204;204;204muser desktop env, and gohash_binary identifies the executable as the system python binary hash\u001b[m                                \u001b[K\r\n \u001b[38;2;204;204;204mfca712f4e2721b0a465d162ce6779b213d05ed145d906a336ff57210fcc552af.\u001b[0m                                                             \u001b[K\r\n \u001b[38;2;204;204;204m\u001b[0m                                                                                                                              \u001b[K\r\n \u001b[38;2;204;204;204mIf you want, I‚Äôll drill into the script on disk and trace this PID for live syscalls next.\u001b[0m                                    \u001b[K\r\n \u001b[1;38;2;0;255;136myou‚ùØ \u001b[0mwant to see memory.                                                                                                      \u001b[K\r\n   \u001b[48;2;204;34;0m \u001b[0m\u001b[1;38;2;255;255;255;48;2;204;34;0m‚¨° read_memory\u001b[0m\u001b[48;2;204;34;0m \u001b[0m  \u001b[3;38;2;153;153;153mPID 264057 @ 0x555d5f42d000 ¬∑ 2624 bytes ¬∑ 98% printable\u001b[0m                                                   \u001b[K\r\n \u001b[1;38;2;255;68;68mgodshell‚ùØ \u001b[0m\u001b[38;2;204;204;204mThe first memory page is clean ELF header from the mapped Python executable, not payload data. Evidence:\u001b[m            \u001b[K\r\n \u001b[38;2;204;204;204mread_memory at 555d5f42d000 begins with 7f 45 4c 46 and matches the executable base from get_maps for /usr/bin/python3.14.\u001b[0m    \u001b[K\r\n \u001b[38;2;204;204;204m\u001b[0m                                                                                                                              \u001b[K\r\n \u001b[38;2;204;204;204mIf you want useful memory, give me which region to target next:\u001b[0m                                                               \u001b[K\r\n \u001b[38;2;204;204;204m1. Heap at 555d94a3b000\u001b[0m                                                                                                       \u001b[K\r\n \u001b[38;2;204;204;204m2. Large anonymous region at 7f14711fe000\u001b[0m                                                                                     \u001b[K\r\n \u001b[38;2;204;204;204m3. Python runtime data near libpython mappings\u001b[0m                                                                                \u001b[K\r\n \u001b[38;2;204;204;204m4. Stack at 7ffef85a1000\u001b[0m                                                                                                      \u001b[K\r\n \u001b[1;38;2;0;255;136myou‚ùØ \u001b[0mmap the memory then target it, i want to read the heap                                                                   \u001b[K\r\n   \u001b[48;2;204;34;0m \u001b[0m\u001b[1;38;2;255;255;255;48;2;204;34;0m‚¨° read_memory\u001b[0m\u001b[48;2;204;34;0m \u001b[0m  \u001b[3;38;2;153;153;153mPID 264057 @ 0x555d94a3b000 ¬∑ 5153 bytes ¬∑ 98% printable\u001b[0m                                                   \u001b[K\r\n \u001b[1;38;2;255;68;68mgodshell‚ùØ \u001b[0m\u001b[38;2;204;204;204mThe heap is live and readable; it currently shows allocator metadata, pointers, and at least one clear string, not\u001b[m  \u001b[K\r\n \u001b[38;2;204;204;204mencrypted or obviously wiped. Evidence: read_memory at heap base 555d94a3b000 returned glibc-style chunk markers like 21 00\u001b[m   \u001b[K\r\n \u001b[38;2;204;204;204m00 00 and many in-heap pointers, plus readable strings \".mo\" and \"en_US.UTF-8\".\u001b[0m                                               \u001b[K\r\n \u001b[38;2;204;204;204m\u001b[0m                                                                                                                              \u001b[K\r\n \u001b[38;2;204;204;204mThe first heap page is not where the interesting payload lives. Evidence: this chunk looks like locale/runtime setup data,\u001b[m    \u001b[K\r\n \u001b[38;2;204;204;204mwhich fits Python startup state more than script content. The better move is to walk deeper into the heap by sampling later\u001b[m   \u001b[K\r\n \u001b[38;2;204;204;204moffsets inside the same mapped heap region 555d94a3b000-555d94bf4000 from get_maps.\u001b[0m                                           \u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "\r\n \u001b[38;2;204;204;204m\u001b[0m                                                                                                                              \u001b[K\r\n \u001b[38;2;204;204;204mSay ‚Äúgo deeper‚Äù and I‚Äôll read a few later heap offsets to hunt for script strings, URLs, commands, or buffers.\u001b[0m                \u001b[K\r\n \u001b[1;38;2;0;255;136myou‚ùØ \u001b[0mokay, go deeper.                                                                                                         \u001b[K\r\n   \u001b[38;2;255;68;68m‚àô‚óè‚àô\u001b[0m \u001b[3;38;2;255;102;85mScanning system snapshot...\u001b[0m                                                                                             \u001b[K\r\n \u001b[1;38;2;0;255;136m‚ùØ \u001b[0m\u001b[7ma\u001b[0m\u001b[38;5;240msk godshell something...\u001b[0m                                                                                                   \u001b[K\r\n \u001b[38;2;85;85;85mCtrl+([r]efresh [s]ave [l]oad [p]anel) type help for more info, Esc to toggle focus\u001b[0m\u001b[38;2;68;68;68m 100%\u001b[0m                                      \u001b[K\r\n \u001b[38;2;0;255;136m[sel:bash ./launch_test_agent.sh/264057]\u001b[0m                                                                                      \u001b[K\u001b[33;H"]
