[0.283, "o", "\u001b[H\n \u001b[1;38;2;255;68;68mgodshell‚ùØ \u001b[0m\u001b[38;2;204;204;204mHeap carving still does not show script secrets or obvious malicious strings. Evidence: 555d94a60000 and\u001b[m            \u001b[K\r\n \u001b[38;2;204;204;204m555d94bc0000 are mostly pointer-heavy Python object arenas; 555d94ac0000 is entirely zeroed in this sample.\u001b[0m                   \u001b[K\r\n \u001b[38;2;204;204;204m\u001b[0m                                                                                                                              \u001b[K\r\n \u001b[38;2;204;204;204mOne region stands out as non-text structured data, but not clearly malicious. Evidence: 555d94b20000 contains dense small-\u001b[m    \u001b[K\r\n \u001b[38;2;204;204;204mvalue words and ff ff markers across the whole page, which looks like packed tables, arrays, or interpreter-internal data\u001b[m     \u001b[K\r\n \u001b[38;2;204;204;204mrather than plaintext commands, URLs, or tokens.\u001b[0m                                                                              \u001b[K\r\n \u001b[38;2;204;204;204m\u001b[0m                                                                                                                              \u001b[K\r\n \u001b[38;2;204;204;204mConclusion: the heap is dominated by Python runtime/object storage, and this snapshot is not exposing human-readable\u001b[m          \u001b[K\r\n \u001b[38;2;204;204;204mpayloads there. Better target now is stack top or the script file itself, because memory carving is yielding internals, not\u001b[m   \u001b[K\r\n \u001b[38;2;204;204;204mintent. Say ‚Äústack top‚Äù or ‚Äúread script‚Äù.\u001b[0m                                                                                     \u001b[K\r\n \u001b[1;38;2;0;255;136myou‚ùØ \u001b[0mstack top                                                                                                                \u001b[K\r\n   \u001b[48;2;204;34;0m \u001b[0m\u001b[1;38;2;255;255;255;48;2;204;34;0m‚¨° read_memory\u001b[0m\u001b[48;2;204;34;0m \u001b[0m  \u001b[3;38;2;153;153;153mPID 264057 @ 0x7ffef85c1000 ¬∑ 5153 bytes ¬∑ 98% printable\u001b[0m                                                   \u001b[K\r\n \u001b[1;38;2;255;68;68mgodshell‚ùØ \u001b[0m\u001b[38;2;204;204;204mThe stack sample is still empty. Evidence: read_memory at 7ffef85c1000 returned all zeroes, just like the lower\u001b[m     \u001b[K\r\n \u001b[38;2;204;204;204mstack read.\u001b[0m                                                                                                                   \u001b[K\r\n \u001b[38;2;204;204;204m\u001b[0m                                                                                                                              \u001b[K\r\n \u001b[38;2;204;204;204mThat means we are not landing on active frames, or the useful stack content sits between the sampled pages. Best next read\u001b[m    \u001b[K\r\n \u001b[38;2;204;204;204mis the middle of the mapped stack, not the ends. Say ‚Äústack middle‚Äù and I‚Äôll hit the center of 7ffef85a1000-7ffef85c2000.\u001b[0m     \u001b[K\r\n \u001b[1;38;2;0;255;136myou‚ùØ \u001b[0mstack middle                                                                                                             \u001b[K\r\n   \u001b[48;2;204;34;0m \u001b[0m\u001b[1;38;2;255;255;255;48;2;204;34;0m‚¨° read_memory\u001b[0m\u001b[48;2;204;34;0m \u001b[0m  \u001b[3;38;2;153;153;153mPID 264057 @ 0x7ffef85b1000 ¬∑ 10209 bytes ¬∑ 98% printable\u001b[0m                                                  \u001b[K\r\n \u001b[1;38;2;255;68;68mgodshell‚ùØ \u001b[0m\u001b[38;2;204;204;204mThe mapped stack is effectively empty in every sampled page. Evidence: reads at 7ffef85a1000, 7ffef85b1000, and\u001b[m     \u001b[K\r\n \u001b[38;2;204;204;204m7ffef85c1000 all returned zero-filled pages despite get_maps showing a 132 KB [stack] region.\u001b[0m                                 \u001b[K\r\n \u001b[38;2;204;204;204m\u001b[0m                                                                                                                              \u001b[K\r\n \u001b[38;2;204;204;204mThat is abnormal enough to flag, but I can‚Äôt say why from snapshot alone. Theory: either this thread‚Äôs useful stack content\u001b[m   \u001b[K\r\n \u001b[38;2;204;204;204msits outside the sampled windows due to guard/lazy pages, or the snapshot exposes a zeroed view of stack memory. Memory\u001b[m       \u001b[K\r\n \u001b[38;2;204;204;204mreads are not giving us userland strings here.\u001b[0m                                            "]
